[normal]2.1
[normal]              
[normal]Limited liability partnerships (LLPs) were introduced a
[normal]s a 
[normal]legal entity 
[normal]in 2000.  The intention was to provide a commercial entity that had some limited liability protection for its members but with the taxati
[normal]on attributes of partnerships.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.2
[normal]              
[normal]Partnership taxation treatment is fundamental to LLPs.  If LLPs we
[normal]re taxed as companies the LLP structure would serve 
[normal]limited
[normal] purpose and 
[normal]many 
[normal]professional firms would operate as limited companies or as traditional partnerships under the 1890 
[normal]A
[normal]ct.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.3
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]original 
[normal]drafting of the tax legislation of LLPs (now 
[normal]s
[normal]863 ITTOIA 2005) was not consulted upon at the time.  This lack of consultation led to defective legislation that the Government is now trying to correct (and 
[normal]again, 
[normal]in our view
[normal],
[normal] with insufficient consultation)
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.4
[normal]              
[normal]We understand that the original intenti
[normal]on was for LLPs to be taxed as if partnerships, and therefore a member
[normal]’
[normal]s tax status would be the same as that 
[normal]within 
[normal]an 1890 
[normal]A
[normal]ct partnership.
[normal]  This intention was confirmed by HMRC at paragraph 2.8 in the 20 May 2013 Consultation Document.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.5
[normal]              
[normal]‘
[normal]Salaried pa
[normal]rtners
[normal]’
[normal] of an 1890 
[normal]A
[normal]ct partnership are employees with the title 
[normal]‘
[normal]partner
[normal]’
[normal] but who are not partners.  The LLP 
[normal]A
[normal]ct allows for members of an LLP to also be employees.  The tax legislation (through erroneous drafting in our view) conferred self-employed tax st
[normal]atus as if true partners on employe
[normal]e
[normal] members.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]2.6
[normal]              
[normal]Members of our tax committee, and other practitioners, highlighted this anomaly to HMRC at the time and explained that we anticipated that the defects in this legislation
[normal] would be
[normal] exploited.  It is frustra
[normal]ting that appropriate debate did not take place over a decade ago, 
[normal]tha
[normal]t our predictions 
[normal]have 
[normal]come true
[normal] (indeed beyond even our expectations)
