[normal]4.3
[normal]              
[normal]Unfortunately the HMRC 
[normal]‘
[normal]technical notes and guidance
[normal]’
[normal] of 10 December make it clear that we have been prese
[normal]nted a fait accompli.  "The Government would not expect to make significant changes to the published legislation, although 
[normal]comments on 
[normal]technical details would be welcome."
[normal]  
[normal](Page 3 of HMRC’s Technical Note and Guidance 10 December 2013.)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.4
[normal]              
[normal]The 
[normal]impression being strongly given is that there is no intention on the part of Government to debate the principles behind the fresh proposals.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]5
[normal]              
[normal]The revised proposals will not catch some employee members who the Government clearly wished to tax as 
[normal]employees within their original proposals.  Under the new proposals it is quite possible the low paid workers referred to in paragraph 2.9 of the 20 May consultation document will under the new proposals be able to remain self-employed
[normal] if their arrangement
[normal]s are set up so to do
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]6
[normal]              
[normal]In contrast there were 
[normal]individuals 
[normal]not intended to be affected by the original proposals, who now may well be
[normal].  F
[normal]or example
[normal],
[normal] "junior partners (who) are substantially rewarded by a fixed profit share" where paragraph 2.13 of the 
[normal]20 
[normal]M
[normal]ay consultation document suggested it would be appropriate
[normal] for them
[normal] to remain as self-employed
[normal], but who are now potentially to be caught
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]7
[normal]              
[normal]Many professional firms with junior members now find that the tax position of those members may well change o
[normal]n 6 April 2014 and they have no opportunity to enter into any meaningful debate about the proposals.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.8
[normal]              
[normal]The same is true of firms where members share profits primarily by a 
[normal]percentage
[normal] of 
[normal]the
[normal] profits
[normal] of a division of the firm
[normal].  Under the 20 May 2013 doc
[normal]ument proposals our understanding is that this would be a variable profit share and the individuals would not be classed as salaried members.  The draft Finance Bill clauses completely change the outcome in this regard as a share of a divisions profits is 
[normal]to be classed as ‘disguised salary’ (although clearly variable the problem is that it does not directly vary with the firm’s overall profits, only the divisions).
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]9
[normal]              
[normal]The timescale of implementation by 6 April 2014 is now so short that those firms who fin
[normal]d themselves affected
[normal],
[normal] and previously assumed they would 
[normal]not
[normal],
[normal] find that they have no time to debate
[normal] the position.
[normal]  Some quite fundamental principles have changed as we have explained above.
[normal] 
[normal] 
[normal]The focus of potentially affected firms
[normal] is on attempting to minimise the 
[normal]impact of 
[normal]what they believe to be inappropriate change to tax legislation.
[normal]  With our self-assessment regime they will face interest and penalties for failing to operate PAYE if appropriate on members’ income from 6 April 2
[normal]014
[normal], even though the legislation will not receive Royal Assent until summer 2014 and may change through parliamentary process in the meantime
[normal].
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.10
[normal]              
[normal]For some individual members the proposed legislation even has an impact upon the tax due from them on 31 Ja
[normal]nuary 2014.  If they otherwise expect their tax liability for 2013/14 to be lower than for 2012/13 then they are able to make a ‘payment reduction claim’ to reduce their 2013/14 interim payments on account (with the first instalment due on 31 January 2014)
[normal].  However, if they are treated as ceasing self
[normal]-
[normal]employment on 5 April 2014 on 
[normal]becoming
[normal] a salaried member on 6 April 2014 (see 4.
[normal]12 
[normal]b
[normal]elow) they might have a higher 2013/14 tax liability as a result, and would then be liable to interest on what then proves t
[normal]o be an underpaid first instalment of tax 
[normal]due 
[normal]on 31
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]January 2014.
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.11
[normal]              
[normal]Where an individual has sufficient capital in the firm on 6 April 2014 they will be able to continue to be treated as self-employed.  Currently the draft legislation insists that any c
[normal]apital commitment made to the firm only counts to the extent it is paid in to the firm by the relevant date.  Banks are already warning that they face administrative difficulty in processing demand 
[normal]from individual members 
[normal]for additional loans 
[normal]to subscribe 
[normal]capital 
[normal]by Friday 4 April 2014 (the last working day before 6 April).  Is it right that a bank’s ability to process applications should determine an individual’s tax status?  (We have suggested to HMRC that a ‘window of opportunity’ be given for the commit
[normal]ted capital to be paid in.)
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.1
[normal]2
[normal]              
[normal]The draft Finance Bill clauses clearly treat salaried members as employees for tax purposes from 6 April 2014.  The HMRC guidance 
[normal]does not explain whether self
[normal]-
[normal]employment status is deemed to cease on 5 April 2014 or on 6 A
[normal]pril 2014.
[normal]  In tax terms this is not a difference of a day but of a whole year.  Does one cease in 2013/14 or in 2014/15?
[normal]&#xa0;
[normal]4.
[normal]1
[normal]3
[normal]              
[normal]In drafting the proposed new legislation HMRC 
[normal]f
[normal]a
[normal]c
[normal]ed a choice of adopting our recommendation (to bring existing partnership case 
[normal]law into play
